    }
  ],
  "computational_details": [],
  "unmapped_findings": [
    "With increasing Cr content, ferrite volume fraction increases from 10.2 vol% (0Cr) to 19.6 vol% (9Cr), morphology changes from rod-like to block-like",
    "Cr addition increases strain hardening rate of as-cast strips, average values are 1626 MPa, 2048 MPa, 2266 MPa and 2385 MPa for 0Cr, 3Cr, 6Cr, 9Cr respectively",
    "DO3 phase precipitates in ferrite of as-cast 6Cr and 9Cr strips, and appears in all strips after annealing",
    "After annealing at 550℃ for 5h, κ-carbide precipitation increases in 0Cr strip, but is still suppressed in Cr-containing strips",
    "After tensile fracture, average slip band spacing is ~90 nm (as-cast 0Cr), ~80 nm (as-cast 6Cr), ~190 nm (annealed 0Cr), ~60 nm (annealed 6Cr)",
    "For 3Cr strips annealed at 550℃, κ-carbides mainly precipitate within the first 1 hour, while dislocation recovery requires longer annealing time",
    "Initial dislocation density has significant influence on elongation of the steel, besides slip band formation ability during deformation"
  ]
